26nbsp;[1;35m\\[0m[31mu0026nbsp;[1;35m\\[0m[31mu0026nbsp;  Liberty and equality.[1;35m\\[0m[31mr[1;35m\\[0m[31mn| Chapter 11|[1;35m\\[0m[31mu0026nbsp;[1;35m\\[0m[31mu0026nbsp;[1;35m\\[0m[31mu0026nbsp;[1;35m\\[0m[31mu0026nbsp;[1;35m\\[0m[31mu0026nbsp;[1;35m\\[0m[31mu0026nbsp;   Justice.[1;35m\\[0m[31mr[1;35m\\[0m[31mn| Chapter 12|[1;35m\\[0m[31mu0026nbsp;[1;35m\\[0m[31mu0026nbsp;[1;35m\\[0m[31mu0026nbsp;[1;35m\\[0m[31mu0026nbsp;[1;35m\\[0m[31mu0026nbsp;[1;35m\\[0m[31mu0026nbsp;  Ethics and politics in modernity. [1;35m\\[0m[31mr[1;35m\\[0m[31mn[1;35m\\[0m[31mr[1;35m\\[0m[31mn####**Workload**[1;35m\\[0m[31mr[1;35m\\[0m[31mnMy teaching method aims primarily at defining and discussing concepts, not at illustrating authors or providing historical narratives; needless to say, there will be enough reference to authors, books, events and processes, in particular with regard to the evolution of political modernity. For each of the twelve lectures of about 30-40', which will be presented in shorter units, you may need three more hours of homework to do additional readings and - more importantly - to perform additional reflection.[1;35m\"[0m[31m,[1;35m\"[0m[31mstart_date[1;35m\"[0m[31m:[1;35m\"[0m[31m2014-10-14T12:56:00.000+02:00[1;35m\"[0m[31m,[1;35m\"[0m[31mend_date[1;35m\"[0m[31m:[1;35m\"[0m[31m2015-01-20T13:32:00.000+01:00[1;35m\"[0m[31m,[1;35m\"[0m[31mstate[1;35m\"[0m[31m:[1;35m\"[0m[31mactive[1;35m\"[0m[31m,[1;35m\"[0m[31mimage[1;35m\"[0m[31m:[1;35m\"[0m[31mhttps://d1wshrh2fwv7ib.cloudfront.net/courses/9bd8e13b-8c20-4e68-bc04-7d23df9080b2/70334302194340.jpg[1;35m\"[0m[31m},{[1;35m\"[0m[31mid[1;35m\"[0m[31m:167,[1;35m\"[0m[31mtitle[1;35m\"[0m[31m:[1;35m\"[0m[31mCritical Thinking - Reason and Fair Play in Communication[1;35m\"[0m[31m,[1;35m\"[0m[31msubtitle[1;35m\"[0m[31m:[1;35m\"[0m[31mA fun journey through the mechanism of reasoning and argumentation, illustrated by tons of documented experiments and interesting examples. [1;35m\"[0m[31m,[1;35m\"[0m[31mdescription[1;35m\"[0m[31m:[1;35m\"[0m[31m####**Course Summary**[1;35m\\[0m[31mr[1;35m\\[0m[31mnThis MOOC is an introduction in Critical Thinking, with an emphasis on using reason in our daily communication. Its main topics cover the structure and analysis of arguments, the study of inductive reasoning as basis for scientific knowledge and as key ingredient in how we understand reality. Next we will focus on fallacies (like loaded question or hasty generalization) and on guidelines for structuring a presentation, an argumentative essay or a debate. Furthermore, the course gives you an overview of cognitive biases (a fashionable topic nowadays), and on the use of emotional tools in persuasion. The teaching is accompanied by tons of documented experiments and fun examples, guided practice, quizzes, links to additional materials (like TED talks) and short homework.[1;35m\\[0m[31mr[1;35m\\[0m[31mn[1;35m\\[0m[31mr[1;35m\\[0m[31mn####**What do I learn?**[1;35m\\[0m[31mr[1;35m\\[0m[31mnAfter taking this course you will have the tools to analyze the truth of all kinds of statements, from opinion articles to court verdicts and investment proposals. You will better understand the philosophical basis of human knowledge, also you will be more persuasive in domestic talks as well as in good structured presentations, debates or argumentative essays. Furthermore, a main goal of this course is that you will be able to recognize and refute the most common fallacies (reasoning errors), and understand irrational behavior.[1;35m\\[0m[31mr[1;35m\\[0m[31mn[1;35m\\[0m[31mr[1;35m\\[0m[31mn####**What do I need to know?**[1;35m\\[0m[31mr[1;35m\\[0m[31mnNo prior knowledge is needed for this course, participants should only come equipped with natural curiosity and a respect for the truth.[1;35m\\[0m[31mr[1;35m\\[0m[31mn[1;35m\\[0m[31mr[1;35m\\[0m[31mn####**Course Structure**[1;35m\\[0m[31mr[1;35m\\[0m[31mn[1;35m\\[0m[31mr[1;35m\\[0m[31mn**Chapter [1;35m\\[0m[31mu0026 Topic** [1;35m\\[0m[31mr[1;35m\\[0m[31mn[1;35m\\[0m[31mr[1;35m\\[0m[31mn**Chapter 1:[1;35m\\[0m[31mu0026nbsp;Introduction to Critical Thinking** - what is critical thinking, why study it, a short history [1;35m\\[0m[31mr[1;35m\\[0m[31mn1.1: Road Map[1;35m\\[0m[31mr[1;35m\\[0m[31mn1.2: Is Man the Reasoning Animal?[1;35m\\[0m[31mr[1;35m\\[0m[31mn1.3: Critical Thinking. Some Definitions and a Short History[1;35m\\[0m[31mr[1;35m\\[0m[31mn[1;35m\\[0m[31mr[1;35m\\[0m[31mn**Chapter 2:[1;35m\\[0m[31mu0026nbsp;Arguments ABC** - understanding arguments as building blocks of reason; argument structure and analysis[1;35m\\[0m[31mr[1;35m\\[0m[31mn2.1: Simple Argument. Definition and Structure[1;35m\\[0m[31mr[1;35m\\[0m[31mn2.2: How to Analyze an Argument[1;35m\\[0m[31mr[1;35m\\[0m[31mn2.3: Simple Argument Analysis. Practice[1;35m\\[0m[31mr[1;35m\\[0m[31mn2.4: Complex Arguments[1;35m\\[0m[31mr[1;35m\\[0m[31mn2.5: The Analysis of Complex Arguments[1;35m\\[0m[31mr[1;35m\\[0m[31mn[1;35m\\[0m[31mr[1;35m\\[0m[31mn**Chapter 3:[1;35m\\[0m[31mu0026nbsp;Deductive vs. Inductive, or Definitely vs. Probably** - describing and analysing the two main types of arguments[1;35m\\[0m[31mr[1;35m\\[0m[31mn3.1: Deductive Arguments vs. Inductive Arguments[1;35m\\[0m[31mr[1;35m\\[0m[31mn3.2: Deductive Arguments. Validity. Soundness[1;35m\\[0m[31mr[1;35m\\[0m[31mn3.3: Syllogisms[1;35m\\[0m[31mr[1;35m\\[0m[31mn3.4: Inductive Arguments. Strength. Cogency[1;35m\\[0m[31mr[1;35m\\[0m[31mn[1;35m\\[0m[31mr[1;35m\\[0m[31mn**Chapter 4:[1;35m\\[0m[31mu0026nbsp;Inductive Reasoning** - the scientific method as basis for all sciences; a short instructions manual on the use of inductive reasoning in day to day communication[1;35m\\[0m[31mr[1;35m\\[0m[31mn4.1: The Scientific Theory. Is It All Just Guessing?[1;35m\\[0m[31mr[1;35m\\[0m[31mn4.2: The Scientific Method[1;35m\\[0m[31mr[1;35m\\[0m[31mn4.3: Arguments from Analogy[1;35m\\[0m[31mr[1;35m\\[0m[31mn4.4: Arguments from Generalisation[1;35m\\[0m[31mr[1;35m\\[0m[31mn4.5: Arguments from Causality[1;35m\\[0m[31mr[1;35m\\[0m[31mn[1;35m\\[0m[31mr[1;35m\\[0m[31mn**Chapter 5:[1;35m\\[0m[31mu0026nbsp;Fallacies** - tricky arguments that seem right, but are not; how to spot them and call them out using fancy Latin names; 10 fair play rules[1;35m\\[0m[31mr[1;35m\\[0m[31mn5.1: 10 Fair Play Principles in Argumentation[1;35m\\[0m[31mr[1;35m\\[0m[31mn5.2: Fallacies[1;35m\\[0m[31mr[1;35m\\[0m[31mn5.3: Fallacies (again)[1;35m\\[0m[31mr[1;35m\\[0m[31mn5.4: Name That Fallacy![1;35m\\[0m[31mr[1;35m\\[0m[31mn[1;35m\\[0m[31mr[1;35m\\[0m[31mn**Chapter 6:[1;35m\\[0m[31mu0026nbsp;Argumentation** - how to structure essays, presentations, and debates; how to use and quote sources[1;35m\\[0m[31mr[1;35m\\[0m[31mn6.1: Argumentative Essay[1;35m\\[0m[31mr[1;35m\\[0m[31mn6.2: Debates and Other Oral Arguments[1;35m\\[0m[31mr[1;35m\\[0m[31mn6.3: Presentations[1;35m\\[0m[31mr[1;35m\\[0m[31mn6.4: Credibility and Sources[1;35m\\[0m[31mr[1;35m\\[0m[31mn[1;35m\\[0m[31mr[1;35m\\[0m[31mn**Chapter 7:[1;35m\\[0m[31mu0026nbsp;Irrationality. Cognitive Biases. Emotional Approach** - what[1;35m\xE2[0m[31m[1;35m\x80[0m[31m[1;35m\x99[0m[31ms going on when we are irrational?; what is the place of emotions in persuasion?[1;35m\\[0m[31mr[1;35m\\[0m[31mn7.1: Cognitive Biases[1;35m\\[0m[31mr[1;35m\\[0m[31mn7.2: Cognitive Biases[1;35m\\[0m[31mr[1;35m\\[0m[31mn7.3: Persuasion. The Emotional Tools[1;35m\\[0m[31mr[1;35m\\[0m[31mn7.4: Conclusions[1;35m\\[0m[31mr[1;35m\\[0m[31mn[1;35m\\[0m[31mr[1;35m\\[0m[31mn####**Workload**[1;35m\\[0m[31mr[1;35m\\[0m[31mnApproximately 2 hours per week for watching video lectures, taking quizzes and completing homework assignments. [1;35m\"[0m[31m,[1;35m\"[0m[31mstart_date[1;35m\"[0m[31m:[1;35m\"[0m[31m2014-11-04T13:00:00.000+01:00[1;35m\"[0m[31m,[1;35m\"[0m[31mend_date[1;35m\"[0m[31m:[1;35m\"[0m[31m2015-01-13T15:54:00.000+01:00[1;35m\"[0m[31m,[1;35m\"[0m[31mstate[1;35m\"[0m[31m:[1;35m\"[0m[31mactive[1;35m\"[0m[31m,[1;35m\"[0m[31mimage[1;35m\"[0m[31m:[1;35m\"[0m[31mhttps://d1wshrh2fwv7ib.cloudfront.net/courses/bfd49694-2294-4fc4-89f7-7d36283595c2/70292539090520.jpg[1;35m\"[0m[31m},{[1;35m\"[0m[31mid[1;35m\"[0m[31m:115,[1;35m\"[0m[31mtitle[1;35m\"[0m[31m:[1;35m\"[0m[31mGovernance and Policy Advice: How Political Decisions Come to Life[1;35m\"[0m[31m,[1;35m\"[0m[31msubtitle[1;35m\"[0m[31m:[1;35m\"[0m[31mWhat happens [1;35m\xE2[0m[31m[1;35m\x80[0m[31m[1;35m\x98[0m[31mbehind the scenes[1;35m\xE2[0m[31m[1;35m\x80[0m[31m[1;35m\x99[0m[31m of political decisions? Who advises politicians, and how big is their influence? Sign up and learn more about policy advice, political consulting and their impact on governance.[1;35m\"[0m[31m,[1;35m\"[0m[31mdescription[1;35m\"[0m[31m:[1;35m\"[0m[31m####**Course Summary**[1;35m\\[0m[31mr[1;35m\\[0m[31mn[1;35m\\[0m[31mr[1;35m\\[0m[31mnPolitical decisions are of course made by governments and/or parliaments. But who provides these bodies with the information they need and shows them the strategic options they have? Who frames political action before the wider public even takes notice of the issue? How does political agenda setting work and what do certain policy outcomes tell us about the future of the issue at stake?[1;35m\\[0m[31mr[1;35m\\[0m[31mnThis course is designed to outline key features of policy advice and political consulting and their impact on governance.[1;35m\\[0m[31mr[1;35m\\[0m[31mnWe will observe the key players on the spot as well as those behind the scenes and we will analyze their patterns of interaction. Moreover, we will provide insights regarding essential questions to which there are no single right answers: What role does policy advice play in different democracies? What is good policy advice? What makes an expert? In sum: Whom do (and should) politicians and society listen to, and what do (and should) they make of the advice they receive?[1;35m\\[0m[31mr[1;35m\\[0m[31mn[1;35m\\[0m[31mr[1;35m\\[0m[31mn####**What do I learn?**[1;35m\\[0m[31mr[1;35m\\[0m[31mn[1;35m\\[0m[31mr[1;35m\\[0m[31mnBy the end of the course, students will know the key concepts of policy advice as well as the main actors in the field and their patterns of interaction. They will understand how and by whom a certain political decision is framed, shaped and implemented. And they will be able to apply this knowledge to a given political event which may affect their own professional or personal life. So, first and foremost, they will be able to ask the right questions.[1;35m\\[0m[31mr[1;35m\\[0m[31mn[1;35m\\[0m[31mr[1;35m\\[0m[31mn####**What do I need to know?**[1;35m\\[0m[31mr[1;35m\\[0m[31mn[1;35m\\[0m[31mr[1;35m\\[0m[31mnThe course is designed to cater for students and professionals who are interested in decision making, political communication, policy advice, and consulting. Course participants are expected to follow current politics and to be keen on looking at the matter from different (and sometimes unusual) perspectives. Basic knowledge in political science would be an asset.[1;35m\\[0m[31mr[1;35m\\[0m[31mn[1;35m\\[0m[31mr[1;35m\\[0m[31mn####**Course Structure**[1;35m\\[0m[31mr[1;35m\\[0m[31mn[1;35m\\[0m[31mr[1;35m\\[0m[31mn[1;35m\\[0m[31mr[1;35m\\[0m[31mn**Chapter 1 [1;35m\\[0m[31mu0026nbsp;[1;35m\\[0m[31mu0026nbsp;[1;35m\\[0m[31mu0026nbsp;[1;35m\\[0m[31mu0026nbsp;[1;35m\\[0m[31mu0026nbsp;[1;35m\\[0m[31mu0026nbsp;     Introduction and Course Overview**[1;35m\\[0m[31mr[1;35m\\[0m[31mnConvener: Prof. Dr. Andrea R[1;35m\xC3[0m[31m[1;35m\xB6[0m[31mmmele, Professor for Communication in Politics [1;35m\\[0m[31mu0026 Civil Society, Hertie School of Governance[1;35m\\[0m[31mr[1;35m\\[0m[31mn[1;35m\\[0m[31mr[1;35m\\[0m[31mn**Chapter 2 [1;35m\\[0m[31mu0026nbsp;[1;35m\\[0m[31mu0026nbsp;[1;35m\\[0m[31mu0026nbsp;[1;35m\\[0m[31mu0026nbsp;[1;35m\\[0m[31mu0026nbsp;[1;35m\\[0m[31mu0026nbsp;   Truth to Power? Scientific Advisers Seeking Truth, Decision-Makers Seeking Power?**[1;35m\\[0m[31mr[1;35m\\[0m[31mnConvener: PD Dr. Martin Thunert, Senior Lecturer, Heidelberg Center for American Studies, University of Heidelberg[1;35m\\[0m[31mr[1;35m\\[0m[31mn[1;35m\\[0m[31mr[1;35m\\[0m[31mn**Chapter 3 [1;35m\\[0m[31mu0026nbsp;[1;35m\\[0m[31mu0026nbsp;[1;35m\\[0m[31mu0026nbsp;[1;35m\\[0m[31mu0026nbsp;[1;35m\\[0m[31mu0026nbsp;[1;35m\\[0m[31mu0026nbsp;   Political Communication and Political Consulting**[1;35m\\[0m[31mr[1;35m\\[0m[31mnConvener: Prof. Dr. Andrea R[1;35m\xC3[0m[31m[1;35m\xB6[0m[31mmmele, Professor for Communication in Politics [1;35m\\[0m[31mu0026 Civil Society, Hertie School of Governance[1;35m\\[0m[31mr[1;35m\\[0m[31mn[1;35m\\[0m[31mr[1;35m\\[0m[31mn**Chapter 4 [1;35m\\[0m[31mu0026nbsp;[1;35m\\[0m[31mu0026nbsp;[1;35m\\[0m[31mu0026nbsp;[1;35m\\[0m[31mu0026nbsp;[1;35m\\[0m[31mu0026nbsp;[1;35m\\[0m[31mu0026nbsp;   Economic and Financial Policy**[1;35m\\[0m[31mr[1;35m\\[0m[31mnConvener: Prof. Dr. Thomas K[1;35m\xC3[0m[31m[1;35m\xB6[0m[31mnig, Chair of Political Science, University of Mannheim[1;35m\\[0m[31mr[1;35m\\[0m[31mn[1;35m\\[0m[31mr[1;35m\\[0m[31mn**Chapter 5 [1;35m\\[0m[31mu0026nbsp;[1;35m\\[0m[31mu0026nbsp;[1;35m\\[0m[31mu0026nbsp;[1;35m\\[0m[31mu0026